title: Desktop Nyaa.si Torrent Uploader/Batch Torrent Uploader
description:
Not coded by me, I paid someone 4 years ago to do this. I decided two years ago to share this on Github (https://github.com/JoGaTo/nyaa.si-batch-uploader).

This is an offline/desktop version of uploading torrents to nyaa.si. It's also the ONLY program to mass upload a hundred torrents at a time, and comes with everything you see below:
![](https://cdn-images.imagevenue.com/9b/d2/c5/ME14XG6N_o.png)

A few things
***
If batch uploading, whatever you put for category, description, and info will be the same to EVERY torrent.
Unclicking the 'Upload to Sukebei' box will allow you to upload to the normal version of the site.


Errors or Problems
***
As much as I prefer to answer your questions to the best of my ability here (cuz, like I said, I ain't the one that coded this and the guy who did I haven't contacted him 4 years since) I would prefer to comment in Github.

This is ONE error that I discovered yesterday that apparently has been going on since late 2021 (before that the software was working fine for four years), and it was every time I tried to upload a torrent, this pops up `request to https://nyaa.si/api/upload failed, reason: certificate has expired` I don't know if it's the fault of the website or the actual software.

description:

>FileBot is the ultimate tool for renaming and organizing your movies, TV shows and Anime. Match and rename media files against online databases, download artwork and cover images, fetch subtitles, write metadata, and more, all at once in seconds. It's smart and just works.
___

This tool is handy for those anime content hoarders who like to keep their content organized and sync with Plex or any kind of Home Media Server. I don't know if it's allowed here or not. But I guess we will find out later. I found this working patch on an underground cracker forum. To my luck, it's the latest version and I have tested it and it works well with no bugs. 

[VirusTotal Result of the Patch](https://www.virustotal.com/gui/file/f58fad3e2e8ad4c0cdd72f1e20428e4bfcac8d927ab0690a40eecd74ba6b4c77)

![alt text](https://i.imgur.com/zLnoK3X.png "FileBot")

**Instructions to use the patch**

Note: Make sure you have the latest Java Runtime Environment  Installed.

*1. Install FileBotx64.msi*

*2. Run the Keymaker.jar*

*3. Navigate to the Folder of the FileBot Director i.e C:\Program Files\FileBot\jar*

*4. Click on Patch*

And you are done !

title: 1 comment
description:
Not to be confused with Azumanga Daioh, the original books titled "Azumanga" are collections of Azuma Kiyohiko's early work circa 1998~2002.

Recently I've gotten a hold of both of these books, and while I would love to scan all of them, unfortunately these are for my personal collection and I am not looking to break their bindings. (Plus the first Azumanga collection is a big coffee table-sized book and doesn't fit on my scanner anyway...)

However these books do include bonus CD-ROMs, which I am sharing with you right now. I've ripped them into basic .iso files, but once mounted you'll find that they're each a big file directory filled with early Y2K-style Japanese webpages, which is pretty neat. I believe most of what's included are what was shown on Azuma's website back in the day, along with some scans of other materials. The first disc is tiny, both in terms of file and physical size, but the second disc includes a lot more stuff, even a couple of video clips and some desktop icon packs.

The second disc features content from Wallaby and Try! Try! Try!, which is a prototype of Yotsuba&!. I haven't gone through the entirety of the discs myself, so feel free to take a look around and share any neat tidbits you can find.

While I cannot scan the books themselves, I did scan the discs and the sleeves they were contained in, so I've included those.

For maximum immersion I recommend you load these ISOs into a Japanese Windows XP VM.
